      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0886">
               <p>Samuel was the only son of <persName>John Gumley</persName>, Muster-master General
                  (d. <date when="1728">1728</date>). He became a lieutenant in the Duke of
                  Marlborough&apos;s Regiment of Dragoons in <date when="1718">1718</date>, a
                  captain in <date when="1724">1724</date>, and a major in <date when="1740"
                     >1740</date>. In <date when="1742">1742</date> he became lieutenant colonel in
                  the First Regiment of Foot Guards (later the Grenadier Guards), and their colonel
                  in <date when="1748">1748</date>. He inherited his mother&apos;s considerable
                  estate, and resigned his military office in <date when="1753-11">Nov. 1753</date>,
                  though he retained his title. By this time he had also acquired a reputation as a
                  pious and earnest supporter of Methodism. He seems to have been officially
                  admitted to membership of the London Society on <date when="1749-04-06">Easter
                     Day, 1749</date>. He died in <placeName>Spa, Belgium</placeName>, in <date
                     when="1763">1763</date>. Samuel&apos;s widow <persName>Martha (Meighen /
                     Colvill) Gumley</persName> (<date from="1711" to="1787">1711–87</date>) was a
                  close friend of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2176.xml"
                  />CW</persName>&apos;s family. See <hi rend="italic">WHS</hi> 59 (<date
                     when="2013">2013</date>): 3–11.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
</TEI>
